default2. To what extent are the needs of different groups of passengers taken into account in d
defaultetermining the provision of public transport to isolated communities? 
default(a) 
defaultPeople with ddefaultisabilitiesdefault 
defaultand young children’s needsdefault 
defaultContracts for supported bus services require operators to use accessible (low floor) vehicles however in the four parish surveys 
defaultabout 33% of respondents gave concern about being able to board the bus as a reason for not using the bus. This is an issue which affects people 
defaultwith disabilities 
default(mostly older people) and parents with young children in pushchairs
default (both groups of people wh
defaulto are very likely to need to use the bus). Although operators are required to provide low floor buses the experience of those responding to the parish surveys is that unsuitable buses are frequently substituted. This undermines confidence in the service. 
default(b) defaultMedical needsdefault: a
defaultmongst the parish survey respondents the second most frequently cited reason for using the bus (after going shopping) was to attend medical appointments. Older people who make up the bulk of rural bus passengers have high non emergency 
defaultmedical needs
default. For the 50% without access to a car their continuing independence may depend on being able to use the bus to get to GP and dental practices and hospital appointments in Hexham. Lack of public transport can lead therefore to premature transfe
defaultr to a care home.
default3. What are the main challenges associated with providing better and more consistent services to isolated communities? How can these challenges be overcome?
default(a)default defaultStimulating demanddefault: t
defaulthe parish surveys referred to above suggest that a key c
defaulthallenge is to identify and capitalise on 
defaultpotentialdefault demand rather than relying wholly on actual bus usage data. 
defaultHow to overcome this
default 
defaultchallenge?
defaultTo release this latent demand and thus increase passenger numbers existing rural bus services need 
default(1) to
default be actively promoted using route branding techniques and widely distributed timetables. This should form part of the contract for any service receiving public support, marketing should also focus on the environmental benefits of using public transport (ju
defaultst as re-cycling is promoted bu most local authorities) 
default(2) to be regular and reliable departing at fixed intervals.
default(3) to be routed to serve key locations including supermarkets and health centres
default(4) to use only low access buses (with no substitution ‘
defaultloop holes’ in the contract.
default(5) to ensure that timetables, once in place, are maintained for as long as possible. 
default(b) defaultTravel to workdefault: 
defaultThe parish surveys indicated that a small but significant number of people 
defaultfrom as far away as Bellingham 
defaultuse the bus to
default get to their place of work. These journeys tend to be in the early morning and in the evening, times when use by other passengers is low. Consequently it is these journeys which are seen as being the least ‘economic’ but most in need of support. 
defaultHow to 
defaultovercome this
default 
defaultchallenge?
defaultUse of a demand responsive service dedicated to this group of users and employing a small vehicle (e.g. 12 or 16 seat) might be appropriate especially as it could be tailored to user’s needs in terms of pick up and connections to o
defaultnward bus and train services from Hexham to Tyneside. 
